\layout Section

Derivation
\layout Standard

This section demonstrates the relationship between the Riemann zeta function
 and the 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{n}$
\end_inset 

, starting from first principles.
 First, the values of the 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{n}$
\end_inset 

 are derived, and then it is shown that the resulting series is equivalent
 to the Riemann zeta function.
 
\layout Standard

The 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{n}$
\end_inset 

 may be derived by a straightforward inversion of a binomial transform.
 Given any sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $\{ s_{n}\}$
\end_inset 

 whatsoever, the binomial transform [ref Knuth concrete math] of this sequence
 is another sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $\{ t_{n}\}$
\end_inset 

, given by 
\begin_inset Formula \[
t_{n}=\sum_{k=0}^{n}(-1)^{k}\left(\begin{array}{c}
s\\
k\end{array}\right)s_{k}\]

\end_inset 

 The binomial transformation is an involution, in that the original series
 is regained by the same transform applied a second time:
\begin_inset Formula \[
s_{n}=\sum_{k=0}^{n}(-1)^{k}\left(\begin{array}{c}
s\\
k\end{array}\right)t_{k}\]

\end_inset 

 A demonstration of the above is straight-forward, in part because each
 sum is finite.
\layout Standard

By assuming the sequence for the Riemann zeta at the integers: 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\zeta(n)=\frac{1}{n-1}+\sum_{k=2}^{n}(-1)^{k}\left(\begin{array}{c}
n\\
k\end{array}\right)b_{k}\]

\end_inset 

 and defining
\begin_inset Formula \[
s_{n}=\zeta(n)-\frac{1}{n-1}\]

\end_inset 

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $n\ge2$
\end_inset 

, while leaving 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{0}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{1}$
\end_inset 

 temporarily indeterminate, one may invert the series as 
\begin_inset Formula \[
b_{n}=s_{0}-ns_{1}+\sum_{k=2}^{n}(-1)^{k}\left(\begin{array}{c}
n\\
k\end{array}\right)\left[\zeta(k)-\frac{1}{k-1}\right]\]

\end_inset 

 The harmonic numbers appear as
\begin_inset Formula \[
\sum_{k=2}^{n}(-1)^{k}\left(\begin{array}{c}
n\\
k\end{array}\right)\frac{1}{k-1}=1-n+nH_{n-1}\]

\end_inset 

 To complete the process, one need only to make the identification 
\begin_inset Formula \[
b_{0}=s_{0}=\lim_{s\to0}\zeta(s)-\frac{1}{s-1}=\zeta(0)+1=\frac{1}{2}\]

\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula \[
s_{1}=\lim_{s\to1}\zeta(s)-\frac{1}{s-1}=\gamma\]

\end_inset 

 Thus, the binomial transform as been demonstrated at the integer values
 of the zeta function.
 
\layout Standard

Next, one must prove that the series 
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{1}{s-1}+\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}(-1)^{n}\,\frac{b_{n}}{n!}\,\left(\begin{array}{c}
s\\
k\end{array}\right)\]

\end_inset 

is identical to the Riemann zeta function for all complex values of 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset 

