A Related Function
\layout Standard

The 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{n}$
\end_inset 

may be further explored by generalizing the parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset 

 to a complex number.
 The 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

obvious
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 and reasonable generalization is 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
b(s)=-s\gamma+\frac{1}{2}+\sum_{k=2}^{\infty}(-1)^{k}\left(\begin{array}{c}
s\\
k\end{array}\right)\left[\zeta(k)-\frac{1}{k-1}\right]\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

By construction, the function 
\begin_inset Formula $b(s)$
\end_inset 

 interpolates the previous series, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $b(n)=b_{n}$
\end_inset 

 for non-negative integers 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset 

.
 This function has a pole at 
\begin_inset Formula $s=-1$
\end_inset 

, and the above series expansion is convergent only for 
\begin_inset Formula $\Re s>-1$
\end_inset 

.
 
\layout Standard

One may ask what form the analytic continuation of 
\begin_inset Formula $b(s)$
\end_inset 

 to the entire complex plane may look like.
 To examine this question, one makes use of two identites.
 
\layout Standard

First, one has 
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \[
\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}(-x)^{k}\left(\begin{array}{c}
s\\
k\end{array}\right)=(1-x)^{s}\]

\end_inset 

 which holds for 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|x\right|<1$
\end_inset 

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset 

.
 When 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset 

 is a positive integer, the sum on the left clearly vanishes in the limit
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x\to1$
\end_inset 

, because the sum consists of a finite number of terms.
 That it also vanishes for any 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset 

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\Re s>0$
\end_inset 

, follows from Carlson's theorem.
 The theorem applies because, for any 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset 

, one can has that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|s\log(1-x)\right|<\pi$
\end_inset 

 in the limit of 
\begin_inset Formula $x\to1$
\end_inset 

.
 Thus, for any 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset 

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\Re s>0$
\end_inset 

, one has 
\begin_inset Formula \[
